    "layout_text": "Natural language layout is the canonical layout authority for the Brief Intake page; inventory records are only an index and validation skeleton. For the desktop carrier the page uses a two column main region inside a full page container: a header region, primary field section, secondary action section, and overlay host. For tablet the same hierarchy reflows to a wider single column with the action group after the required fields. For mobile, mobile iOS, and mobile Material carriers the sections stack vertically with the primary group before secondary recovery copy; iOS respects safe area, system bar, navigation stack, and keyboard constraints, while Material uses app bar, system bar, keyboard inset, and elevation rules. The containment hierarchy has a parent page, child header, child main, nested field group, nested action group, nested state message group, and validation overlay surface. Ordering is explicit: project name before audience, page type before primary user goal, business constraint before validate and generate, recovery actions below failure copy, and final ready below processing results. Sizing states width, height, minimum and maximum readable density constraints; narrow width wraps fields and buttons before any overflow. Height is never used to hide required information: the page uses vertical scroll, sticky action placement when needed, and overflow recovery by expansion. Empty, loading, error, disabled, permission, success, recovery, validation, and final-ready states have placements in the state placement index. Long content growth can wrap, overflow into scroll, truncate only with recovery, expand inside the same page, or paginate only future evidence lists. The z-axis layering uses base, sticky, overlay, modal, loading, toast, and snackbar concepts; overlay.validation blocks lower layers while preserving background context and restoring focus.",
